article.description: Seimone Augustus scored 26 points and top-seeded LSU broke open a tight game with a big second-half run, beating Washington 72-49 in the second round.
article.headline: LSU rolls past Washington to fourth straight Sweet 16
article.linkText: LSU rolls past Washington to fourth straight Sweet 16
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The LSU Lady Tigers are headed to the regional semifinals of the NCAA Tournament, and they are expecting to play even better than they did in the second round.

Seimone Augustus scored 26 points and top-seeded LSU broke open a tight game with a big second-half run, beating Washington 72-49 on Monday night to advance to their fourth straight regional semifinal.

"This is another eye opener for us, and I expect that our level of play will increase and it will pick up as we get into San Antonio," Augustus said.

The Lady Tigers (29-3) will play DePaul, a 71-67 winner over Tulsa, on Saturday in the San Antonio Regional. That's a successful season for most teams, but LSU has its sights on a national championship after reaching the Final Four each of the past two years only to come up short of the final.

"To win going away and not to be on top of our game knowing you can go home and correct those things, I'm OK with that," Lady Tigers coach Pokey Chatman said.

LSU senior Scholanda Hoston said the Lady Tigers brought the struggles on themselves.

"We kind of put ourselves in a hole of not executing the way we're capable. We had to work a lot harder to get back to where we were at the beginning of the game," Hoston said.

Ninth-seeded Washington (19-11) tried to pull off a second straight upset to reach a regional semifinal for the fourth time in school history and first since 2001. The Huskies certainly gave the Southeastern Conference's regular-season champs their best shot.

LSU outrebounded Washington 44-42 only after a late run on the boards in a physical game that sent players flying all over. They also shut out both Augustus and 6-foot-6 center Sylvia Fowles on the boards in the first half. Fowles played only 2 minutes before going to the bench with two fouls.

That helped Washington take a 26-23 lead into halftime.

"You knew that LSU was definitely going to come back with a lot more energy in the second half," Washington coach June Daugherty said.

Even when LSU opened the second half with a 12-2 run, the Huskies wouldn't bow out easily.

Cheri Craddock hit a 3 followed by another 3 from Kristen O'Neill, and Cameo Hicks capped the eight-point spurt with a bucket at 14:01 that put Washington up 38-37. That was the Huskies' last lead as they failed to hit anything other than a pair of free throws until it was way too late.

Augustus scored 61 seconds later to put LSU ahead to stay, starting a 27-6 run that left the Lady Tigers up 64-44 late.

Hoston added 13 points for LSU, and Fowles finished with 10 points and seven rebounds -- all in the second half. Augustus had nine rebounds.

Hicks led Washington with 17 points.

LSU opened the game with an 11-2 run as Washington missed its first five shots. Then the Huskies started doing what they do best -- crashing the boards.

They wound up outrebounding LSU 28-16 through the first half. The Lady Tigers also went cold from the floor after hitting four of their first seven shots. They hit four of their last 22 shots after the strong start.

"We showed a lot of heart and a lot of guts just to keep fighting through the difficult times that we had when Sylvia was out and our offense was struggling," Augustus said. "Just to be within 3 going into half says a lot about us and our character."
